  "id": "purine-de-novo-synthesis",
  "name": "De novo purine nucleotide biosynthesis",
  "category": "nucleotide-metabolism",
  "summary": "Cytosolic pathway that assembles the purine ring stepwise on PRPP to form IMP, then branches to AMP and GMP; each ring is built from glycine, two glutamine amides, one aspartate, two formyl groups from 10-formyl-THF, and CO2.",
  "description": "De novo purine synthesis builds the purine ring directly on the ribose-5-phosphate carrier PRPP, rather than salvaging preformed bases. Ten enzyme-catalysed steps (steps 2–11 here) assemble inosine 5'-monophosphate (IMP), the first complete purine nucleotide, on top of PRPP (made in step 1). The ring atoms have defined origins: N1 from aspartate; C2 and C8 from 10-formyl-tetrahydrofolate; N3 and N9 from the amide of glutamine; C4, C5 and N7 from glycine; and C6 from CO2. Because five of the ten committed reactions consume a high-energy nucleotide (four ATP plus one for PRPP, and one GTP in the AMP branch), assembly of one purine ring to IMP is energetically expensive.\n\nThe first committed and rate-limiting reaction is glutamine phosphoribosyl amidotransferase (PPAT), which is feedback-inhibited synergistically by adenine (AMP/ADP) and guanine (GMP/GDP) nucleotides at separate allosteric sites and driven forward by its substrate PRPP. IMP is then partitioned reciprocally: the AMP branch (adenylosuccinate synthetase + adenylosuccinate lyase) consumes GTP and is feedback-inhibited by AMP, while the GMP branch (IMP dehydrogenase + GMP synthase) consumes ATP and is feedback-inhibited by GMP. Using the energy of the opposite nucleotide balances the adenine/guanine pools. In human cells the six enzymes of the IMP-assembly segment cluster into a dynamic, reversible multienzyme body — the 'purinosome' — that channels intermediates. Several steps are important drug targets: IMPDH (mycophenolate, immunosuppression), GART and ATIC (antifolates such as pemetrexed and methotrexate act partly by starving the two formyl-transfer steps), and the whole pathway is upregulated in proliferating and neoplastic cells.",
  "organisms": ["human"],
  "tissues": ["ubiquitous", "liver", "bone marrow", "proliferating cells"],
  "keywords": ["purine", "IMP", "AMP", "GMP", "PRPP", "purinosome", "de novo nucleotide synthesis", "one-carbon metabolism", "folate"],
